### enum class  {#a66abed31cc3dfac01c8ed560eb6db1c5}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype="enum class llvm::jitlink::aarch32::StubsFlavor "
 labels = {["strong"]}>
AArch32 uses stubs for a number of purposes, like branch range extension or interworking between Arm and Thumb instruction subsets.

<EnumerationList title="Enumeration values">

<Link id="a66abed31cc3dfac01c8ed560eb6db1c5aec0fc0100c4fc1ce4eea230c3dc10360" />
<EnumerationListItem name="Undefined">
 (= 0)
</EnumerationListItem>

<Link id="a66abed31cc3dfac01c8ed560eb6db1c5a25f05cdee23677d484144bcb0c438613" />
<EnumerationListItem name="pre_v7">

</EnumerationListItem>

<Link id="a66abed31cc3dfac01c8ed560eb6db1c5ae6dd71377633723164aeea0750ddafa8" />
<EnumerationListItem name="v7">

</EnumerationListItem>

</EnumerationList>

Stub implementations vary depending on CPU architecture (v4, v6, v7), instruction subset and branch type (absolute/PC-relative).

For each kind of stub, the <a href="#a66abed31cc3dfac01c8ed560eb6db1c5">StubsFlavor</a> defines one concrete form that is used throughout the <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/jitlink/linkgraph">LinkGraph</a>.

Stubs are often called &quot;veneers&quot; in the official docs and online.

Definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/executionengine/include/llvm/executionengine/jitlink/aarch32-h/#l00136">136</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/executionengine/include/llvm/executionengine/jitlink/aarch32-h">aarch32.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>
